WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.920
Can being a little annoyed when trying to access local data end up being

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:12.760
something good? Hi, I'm Sharon Machlis, longtime tech journalist, now retired

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:17.600
mostly, here to hopefully inspire at least some of you on how your data

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:24.600
skills can help your local community. And some good news for the introverts among

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:51.040
us. Okay. Why is this not working? Sorry, everyone, this is my fault. Okay.

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:59.200
There we go. All right, don't take this off my TimeGone person. Okay. So, the

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:04.800
introverts among us, no meetings or long-term commitments required. Instead,

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:10.199
it's just see something, code something. It's combining the fun of solving

00:01:10.199 --> 00:01:15.639
coding challenges with the satisfaction of doing good. What's not to love? So,

00:01:15.639 --> 00:01:19.320
you'll notice some common themes among my projects. These are what I like to do,

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:25.040
help people search and answer questions, and make the web a little easier to use.

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:29.120
Maybe you'd like to do something else, but let's get started. So, there was a

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:33.239
local community group that had a treasure trove of local history in

00:01:33.239 --> 00:01:38.480
decades worth of PDF newsletters, but no way for people to really, like, access

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:44.839
that. So, they did finally post them online, but like this. PDF files in a

00:01:44.839 --> 00:01:50.839
public Google Drive, not really the friendliest of user interfaces, but with

00:01:50.839 --> 00:01:55.879
data skills, we can turn something like that into something like this. Shiny app

00:01:55.879 --> 00:02:02.040
with full-text searching of the newsletter text. And since it's 2025, we

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:06.300
can even add a chatbot, where people can ask natural language questions of the

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:10.679
newsletters, and always I like to include links to the source documents that are

00:02:10.679 --> 00:02:13.960
used to answer the questions, so people can check and make sure that the LLM

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:18.839
didn't just make something up. So, this is the text stack I used for this. For the

00:02:18.839 --> 00:02:24.119
PDF to mark down text, I used LlamaParse. It's a commercial service, but they have

00:02:24.119 --> 00:02:27.559
a generous free tier, and I like the results, but there are other open-source

00:02:27.559 --> 00:02:32.240
options available. Lots of R packages, thanks to all the authors of these.

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:39.000
Ragnar and Elmer for the AI, and Shiny, and ShinyChat, and lots of others. And of

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.919
course, it's 2025, so I did use LLMs to help me write some of the code. I did

00:02:43.919 --> 00:02:48.119
something similar with our city's meeting agendas and minutes. These

00:02:48.119 --> 00:02:53.479
already are full-text searchable, but by individual group. So, if you want to ask a

00:02:53.479 --> 00:02:57.360
question like, what's happening with rail trails around the city, you'd have to

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:01.880
like look in each individual thing. A little bit annoying. So, with data skills,

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:06.479
we can make something like this. Incredibly non-beautiful, but usable. And

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:10.279
in fact, one of our city councilors told me he actually uses this more than the

00:03:10.279 --> 00:03:15.399
official city website, because it searches across. And of course, yes, it's

00:03:15.399 --> 00:03:20.080
this year. I'm trying to add a chatbot also with the source documents. Another

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:24.119
interesting source of local data can be local election data. Now, if you live in a

00:03:24.119 --> 00:03:27.240
large city, chances are there's a newspaper that already does a great job

00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:32.339
with this data, but if you live in a small community, maybe not. This is how my

00:03:32.339 --> 00:03:37.100
city posts its election results. Yes, this is the PDF, and this is the format they

00:03:37.100 --> 00:03:42.259
use. And you'll see this in local media just basically turned into a regular

00:03:42.259 --> 00:03:47.820
table, but with data skills, we could turn that into a map showing where

00:03:47.820 --> 00:03:52.259
candidates were strongest and weakest. A searchable table, maybe with a few

00:03:52.259 --> 00:03:57.940
dataviz elements, maybe even a heat map. So, the tech stack I used for this,

00:03:57.940 --> 00:04:02.899
quarto for publishing, and again, lots of R packages, thanks to all the great

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:08.779
authors of those packages. Maybe your city has a lot of fun things to do,

00:04:08.779 --> 00:04:13.419
but no one place where you can search and sort them. Can you web scrape?

00:04:13.419 --> 00:04:16.500
You could make something like this. Again, not beautiful, but usable,

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:23.019
searchable. Tech stack for this, I'm using Rvest for the web scraping,

00:04:23.019 --> 00:04:27.899
and since I'm reading an RSS feed, also tidy RSS, React table for the table

00:04:27.899 --> 00:04:32.700
display, quarto for publishing, and I'm using a Linux cron job to keep it up to

00:04:32.700 --> 00:04:36.540
date, but GitHub actions would use as well, which are free and you don't need

00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:42.179
your own server. Especially in the US, recycling programs can be kind of

00:04:42.179 --> 00:04:45.980
complicated. Can I recycle this? How do I recycle that? You can feed the whole

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:50.380
thing into a chatbot and let people ask natural language questions. This

00:04:50.380 --> 00:04:53.500
actually can take questions in other languages, since I live in an immigrant

00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:58.540
community. Again, always including the source documents, especially when we're

00:04:58.540 --> 00:05:02.260
doing something, an unofficial app for official data, to make sure people can

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:09.059
check the data. Farmer's markets, who's going to be there? What can I buy there?

00:05:09.059 --> 00:05:12.980
Maybe there's a list of vendors and what they sell. You can make a chatbot and

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:18.660
let people do that. So I hope this gave you some ideas about how your data

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:23.299
skills can help your community. Thanks a lot. Have a great conf.

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:34.320
you

